#. (itstool) path: sect3/para
#: xml/security_preface.xml:346
msgid "Viruses cannot survive and spread without a host on which to live. In this case, the host would be a program or an important storage area of the system (for example, the master boot record) that needs to be writable for the program code of the virus. Because of its multiuser capability, Linux can restrict write access to certain files (this is especially important with system files). Therefore, if you did your normal work with <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> permissions, you would increase the chance of the system being infected by a virus. In contrast, if you follow the principle of using the lowest possible privileges as mentioned above, chances of getting a virus are slim."
